    "tiles": [
      {
        "id": "hdV1HPEbMGfuL1Z2",
        "title": "Text 10",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p><strong>Summarize (Orchestrating the Discussion)</strong></p><p><em>Discussing Solutions and Strategies </em></p><p>Begin by asking general questions to bring out the strategies that your students used.</p><p><strong>Suggested Questions</strong></p><ul><li>How did the percent of students with different traits compare?</li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "3WngC5hF5aeDKt1n",
        "title": "Text 18",
        "display": "teacher",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>Answers will vary. Students might loo at which trait had the largest/smallest percentage; students might compare two traits in for every statements; students might compare the number of students out of 250 for each trait; etc. </p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "fj_XLTjsf9EqsyVP",
        "title": "Text 19",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<ul><li>Which trait had the highest percent in the class? Lowest? </li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "IysEgRb8-YjZtJdb",
        "title": "Text 20",
        "display": "teacher",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>Highest: Straight hair</p><p>Lowest: Dimples</p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "vLZkIC00HvYJU2nX",
        "title": "Text 12",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p><em>Making the Mathematics Explicit </em></p><li>Help students to see why percent is commonly used to compare two comparison statements.</li><li></li><li><strong>Suggested Questions</strong></li><li>Help students to see the advantage of knowing the amount for 1%.</li><ul><li>Why do you think that Marjorie wanted to find the amount represented by 1%?</li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "uY_HPYm66By5sANW",
        "title": "Text 13",
        "display": "teacher",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>Finding 1% is like finding a unit rate. If we know the amount for 1%, we can scale it up to any percent.</p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "KUukVESWiOL2bZTW",
        "title": "Text 15",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>Help students to link the two unit rate strategies to each other. Students can find how many students for 1% of the class, or they ca find how much percentage for 1 student. The strategy you start with will depend on your students—whichever you feel will be accessible to all students in your classroom is probable a good place to begin. (Problem-Solving Environment) </p><p>When discussing What If...? Situation A, <strong>Teaching Aid 4.3: Marjorie Tongue Curling Data</strong> may be helpful.</p><ul><li>If you find 1% of s class, how can you use that information to find what other percents of the class represent? </li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "Y87cBt2wcbOxQmKL",
        "title": "Text 24",
        "display": "teacher",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>Multiply by how many percentages you need to find.</p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "x59IR5M2peH5akOF",
        "title": "Text 21",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<ul><li>If you organized this information in a rate table or diagram, would that help to answer this question? </li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "kU0IPnNU2MyeL4HL",
        "title": "Text 22",
        "display": "teacher",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>Yes, because a visual representation helps to organize the information in order to solve the problem. </p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "lRn9n2Ks4i_ELtAq",
        "display": "teacher",
        "content": {
          "type": "Table",
          "columnWidths": {
            "aoupPRnX79N99MM9": 125.8238525390625,
            "3DZcykXvY7DyGlC4": 119.84017944335938
          }
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "T0EJC9ninGvaFNT6",
        "title": "Text 23",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<ul><li>If you find that 1 student is a certain part of the class, how can you use that information to find the percentage of the class? </li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "dCR0J0G8T5G5vWhF",
        "title": "Text 25",
        "display": "teacher",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>Scale the number of people in the class to 100 to find how much that student represents out of 100. </p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "53BnEMdf_zdjXWJf",
        "title": "Text 26",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<ul><li>If you organized this information in a rate table, would that help answer this question? </li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "MUhK50VbsOu8PIMU",
        "title": "Text 27",
        "display": "teacher",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>Yes, because a rate table provides a visual representation to organize the information in order to solve the problem. </p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
